text: Thank you, North Carolina. I am honored to be your Democratic nominee for U.S. Senate.

Thank you to everyone who is voting and volunteering today, even in the rain! And a special thanks to my family members who are going the extra mile to help our campaign. There’s still time to get to the polls—find your location here: vt.ncsbe.gov/PPLkup/

When you see my name on your ballot, it’s not just me on your ballot: It’s access to health care. It's an investment in public education. It’s taking on climate change. Please don’t wait to make your voice heard. You can find your polling place here: https://vt.ncsbe.gov/PPLkup/

I hear all the time, “Girl, you should run for office!” That’s not my walk. I don’t speak much on politics anymore because I decided to be a mom first. And at the end of the day, teaching is my calling. The closest I’ll get to politics is always advocating. I need to keep my daughters safe and be there for my students. However, every once in awhile someone will reignite my political interest and I become an avid supporter. Cal Cunningham for U.S. Senate is that someone. I’ve watched his career for quite some time. I’ve had several conversations with him and most importantly watched him do the work, from representing families and educators to honoring and supporting students. He is exactly who we need to get things done right and feel safe and secure about North Carolina’s future. I voted for him and I hope you will too!
The ACA has saved lives, but as long as Thom Tillis is in Washington, North Carolinians can’t trust him to defend it. When I’m in the Senate, I will always protect folks with pre-existing conditions.
ICYMI: A new poll in our race has us 5 POINTS ahead of Thom Tillis. We can—and we will—replace him this fall. Help us make sure we’ve got the resources to do it:

Excited to be in Western North Carolina today, and enjoyed lunch with folks in Hendersonville this afternoon. Thank you to Josh Remillard for NC House 117 for hosting us, and for his kind words about our campaign!
Harvey Gantt is a true trailblazer in North Carolina politics. It is such an honor to have his endorsement in this race.

Thank you, Floyd, for your kind words! I’m so thankful to have your support in this race.A Visit by Cal Cunningham to Durham Recently, Cal Cunningham, who is running in the Democratic Primary to become the party’s nominee to run against US Senator Tom Tillis, held a well-attended listening tour here in Durham during which he shared his thoughts and perspectives on the issues facing our state and our country, but, more importantly, he listened to concerns expressed by everyday people right here in our community. I’ve known Cal for close to two decades, and he served our state admirably as a Member of the NC Senate in addition to serving in the military. I would encourage you to read and learn more about his campaign and his capacity to defeat Tom Tillis and to serve our State in Washington.
It’s been a busy week, meeting folks everywhere from Rocky Mount to Chapel Hill to Winston-Salem to Durham. Enjoyed my time in Charlotte tonight—thank you to those who joined us!
11 years ago with Michelle Obama in Fayetteville. I had just gotten back from Iraq and got a call while we were leaving the event I had been selected for the MacArthur award.

This week marks 7 years since Thom Tillis voted to block Medicaid expansion in NC—and since 2010, 7 rural hospitals have closed here. It's a moral issue, and we need to address it. When I’m in the Senate, I’ll work to bring costs down and expand access to care.
More endorsement news: I’m thrilled that The Charlotte Post has endorsed our campaign as we gear up to take on Thom Tillis in November.
Spotted at an early voting site in Wake County. North Carolinians of all species are ready to replace Thom Tillis this fall!

Seven years ago, Thom Tillis passed the bill barring NC's governor from expanding Medicaid. Today, North Carolinians are still suffering the consequences of that decision. When I replace him, I'll fight to expand access to care—not take it away.
Discussed health care, broadband access, our environment and more with small business owners in Durham. Thank you to those who joined us tonight!

One year ago, Thom Tillis wrote a Washington Post op-ed saying he would vote against the president’s sham national emergency. Then he turned around and voted for it anyway, allowing $80m to be diverted from NC military projects.  Today and every day, we deserve better.
Thom Tillis voted to put 1.7 million North Carolinians’ health care in jeopardy—and then called it “courageous.” Health care is on the ballot. We will vote accordingly.
Health care is on the line this fall, and wherever I go I hear from North Carolinians who are concerned about lowering costs and expanding access. We need a Senator who will fight for them.

As my friend Pastor Gailliard put it this morning, we need the right people in public office to move our country forward. I’m so grateful to him for his kind words—and for the opportunity to join the congregation at Word Tabernacle Church today.
Enjoyed a great service at Word Tabernacle Church in Rocky Mount this morning! Thank you to Pastor Gailliard for his kind words—I’m excited to work together to move our state forward.
Thank you, Forsyth County, for the warm welcome earlier today!

Folks all over North Carolina are ready for new representation in the U.S. Senate, and those I spent time with in Winston-Salem this morning are no exception. Enjoyed kicking off the weekend with a great Souls to the Polls event.
Stopped by a polling location in Greensboro this afternoon! Don’t wait to make your voice heard—find your polling place here: https://vt.ncsbe.gov/PPLkup/

Mitch McConnell meddled in our election to try to mislead voters, and it’s clear why—he knows Thom Tillis has failed NC and he’s terrified to face me. I’ve got a message for McConnell and his allies—your scheme won’t work and I’ll see you in November.
I’m humbled by the number of North Carolinians getting involved as we build our coalition. This team is putting in the work needed to beat Thom Tillis in November.
Working together, we’ll beat Thom Tillis—not just because he’s a bad Senator, but because North Carolina deserves better.

We’ve seen Thom Tillis’ priorities—tax cuts and giveaways to the wealthiest people in America—while too many North Carolinians struggle to get ahead. I believe we need different priorities. When I’m in the U.S. Senate, I will always defend Social Security and Medicare.
Looking for a way to get involved in this race? Join us tomorrow to make calls:
Enjoyed my time at UNC Greensboro tonight, talking about the stakes this fall and why it’s so important college students get involved in this election. Thank you to all those who took the time!

Our current representatives have tilted the playing field so far away from fair that many North Carolinians are being left behind. I couldn’t be more proud to have CWA Local 3611's support as we work together to fight for an economy that works for everyone.
It was great to see you, Gwen! Honored to call you a friend.

Everywhere I go, I meet folks who are looking forward to replacing Thom Tillis with a Senator who will listen to them and fight for them. They’re ready for change. Together, we’re going to deliver it. Join us: calfornc.com

Corruption in Washington is one of the greatest threats our country faces—and on issue after issue, Thom Tillis is part of the problem. I’m running to replace him because North Carolinians deserve a leader who will listen to them & fight for them. In the Senate, I always will.

Thank you to folks like Lester and Ann in Fayetteville, and my brother Jake in Charlotte, who are spreading the word about this campaign! I’m so proud to have the support of people all over the state.
A great morning in Durham and Carrboro, talking with folks at precinct meetings about the path forward for North Carolina. Thank you for taking the time!

“We need representatives at all levels of government who are strong supporters of students and teachers and our public schools. And that is why I urge you to choose Cal Cunningham as the candidate for U.S. Senate.”

“Cunningham offers a wider appeal, a diverse coalition of supporters and the most well-funded Democratic campaign, and he does so without compromising Democratic Party values.” I’m honored and grateful to have The Charlotte Observer and The News & Observer’s endorsement.
Voted early with Elizabeth and Caroline—who cast her first-ever ballot. What a special morning!

Thank you for your kind words, John. I’m honored to have your support and your vote!Hey North Carolina! Early voting starts TODAY so I figured I would take this time to remind you to support Cal Cunningham for US Senate!  Cal is the opposite of Thom Tillis, he's a fighter. Cal joined the military after 9/11, leaving his home and going overseas to fight for our country. Cal is a veteran legislator, he was the youngest legislator in North Carolina during his tenure in the NC Senate. Cal is a a businessman, has served on the Governors Crime Commission, and fulfilled many other duties that make him a great choice for US Senate. I was struck the first time I met Cal by his compassion, his thoughtfulness, and his genuine desire to understand the issues people were facing. Cal will do what is right for North Carolina and that's why I'm 100% behind him for election to the United States Senate. Cal is endorsed by the Brady Campaign, End Citizens United, North Carolina Association of Educators, various North Carolina leaders such as Senator Jeff Jackson, fmr. Treasurer Janet Cowell, and was endorsed by the late Senator Kay Hagan.
We should be working to expand North Carolinians’ access to health care—not gut protections and block Medicaid expansion, as Thom Tillis has voted to do.

Thom Tillis is one of the most unpopular Senators in the country—and apparently, Republicans don’t like his chances against me in November. That’s why they’re meddling in our primary. Don’t get fooled.
Campaigning is a family affair! Elizabeth’s mom, Ann, talking with voters in Davidson County last night.
Thank you, Mac! Grateful to have your support.

Thank you to all those who joined us bright and early at the Tuesday Morning Breakfast Forum in Charlotte for a thoughtful discussion on how we can move our state forward. No better way to start the day.
Love this photo—thankful to have your support!

I couldn’t be more honored to be one of Pam’s Picks!Pam's Picks has been posted for the 2020 Watauga County Primary Elections (Democratic Ballot).  If you are a previous reader of Pam's Picks, you may need to refresh your page to clear the google cache to update to this year's election information. Pam's Picks takes a comprehensive look at all the candidates on your 2020 Primary ballot and explains when and where to vote. It also provides my take on "What's at Stake in this Year's Primary Elections." Early voting begins Thursday, February 13th and runs through Saturday, February 29th at all early voting sites (all sites listed on Pam's Picks). Early voting will be open at all sites from 8AM to 7:30PM on weekdays, and from 8AM-3PM on Saturday, February 29th. Election Day is Tuesday, March 3rd. See you at the polls! http://pamspicks.net

I’m ready to get to work partnering with educators across our state to secure the resources needed in our public schools. In the Senate, I’m committed to doing what it takes to give all students the sound, basic education that will allow them to grow and thrive.

I’m a believer that this campaign is about building a relationship with the 10.5 million people who call this state home—because we should be able to count on our elected officials to listen to us & represent us. When I replace Thom Tillis in the Senate, that’s exactly what I’ll do.
Loved the energy from folks in Gaston County. Together, we’re going to replace Thom Tillis next fall.

Had a great evening with folks ahead of the 14th Annual HKonJ People’s Assembly Moral March on Raleigh tomorrow, talking about how together, we will defend the right to vote, expand access to quality, affordable health care, build a fairer economy, and more. Looking forward to tomorrow!

Washington Republicans know Senator Tillis is weak, and apparently they don't like his chances against me in November. Now they’re resorting to shady tactics to meddle in our election—and it’s disrespectful to North Carolina voters. Two of my favorite things: baked goods and talking with North Carolinians about the path forward for our state. Enjoyed a great “cookies and candidates” event in Gastonia tonight!
This is a moral issue. It’s on us to help as many folks as we can get the coverage they deserve. That starts with expanding Medicaid.

North Carolinians know what a fair trial looks like and that’s not what we witnessed. After considering the evidence and the constitutional arguments on both sides, if I were a member of the U.S. Senate, I would vote to convict Donald Trump.

Without coverage for pre-existing conditions, Susie and her family would be bankrupt. Those protections are exactly what Thom Tillis voted to take away. I’m running for U.S. Senate because North Carolinians like Susie deserve a leader who will fight for them.
What happens here this year won’t just be important to North Carolina. It’s going to be important to the whole country.

Thank you to the folks in Cary who took the time to join us yesterday, and for your thoughtful questions on building our economy, ensuring our veterans and military families have the support they deserve, and more.

The ACA is helping folks like those affected by the opioid epidemic get the care they need. In the Senate, I'll work to expand & strengthen the ACA—unlike Sen. Tillis, who proudly said he’d be the 51st vote to repeal it.

What a special night at the Black Political Caucus of Charlotte-Mecklenburg’s 2020 Gala. Enjoyed getting to chat with so many folks, and hearing from keynote speaker Reverend Barber, whose message—on the urgent need for justice and an end to corruption in this country—was powerful and relevant.
Timeout from the campaign trail for a little Canes v Canucks with the fam. Let's go Carolina Hurricanes!
No better way to kick off the month than the Durham Black History Month Parade! Loved being a part of this today.

60 years ago, the Woolworth sit-ins began at a lunch counter in Greensboro. As North Carolinians, our history is fundamentally intertwined with the history of civil rights. Today, we recommit to doing all we can to make true equality & justice a reality in our state.

As a former military prosecutor, I've been clear throughout this process that a fair trial should include witnesses & documents. Thom Tillis refused to give North Carolinians the fair trial we expect.

After 9/11, I took an oath to defend the Constitution. I served overseas in Iraq & Afghanistan. But I never believed the greatest threat to the future of our country would be what we see in Washington, D.C. This year, we have to vote like our future depends on it.
News like this should concern all of us. We need to do more to protect North Carolina’s environment and natural resources.

Thank you to all those who took the time to join us in Durham last night! I’m confident that together, we’re building the coalition it’ll take to send Thom Tillis home and put this seat back to work for North Carolina.
Here in North Carolina, we know what a fair trial looks like. A fair trial has witnesses. A fair trial has documents. If Sen. Tillis was serious about a fair trial, that’s what he would pursue.

Love this photo from last week in Chapel Hill. Every day, I'm reminded of the call to be our brothers’ and sisters’ keepers, and of our shared responsibility to leave this country in a better place for the next generation.
We’ve got a big year ahead, and if the enthusiasm I saw at yesterday’s Women's March On Raleigh was any indication, we’ve got the energy it’ll take to create the change our country needs.
New voter in the Cunningham household. Look out North Carolina, here comes Caroline! Women's March On Raleigh

Enjoyed joining RWCA members in Raleigh this afternoon, where we discussed how we can better ensure North Carolinians have access to the resources and opportunities they deserve. I’m looking forward to working together to build an economy where no one is left behind.

Too many folks struggle with a political system that doesn’t elevate their voices, a health care system that is too costly, & a criminal justice system in need of reform. When I replace Sen. Tillis, I’ll take these challenges on. Glad to discuss it with North Carolina NAACP members today.
On issue after issue, corruption in Washington stands in the way of progress—and Thom Tillis is part of the problem. It’s time for new leadership in this Senate seat.
This race shouldn’t be overlooked—Sen. Tillis is too weak to stand up for our state, and North Carolinians deserve better. We’re ready to vote accordingly this year.

When I joined the Army Reserves and swore to defend the Constitution against all enemies, I never thought that one of the greatest threats to our democracy would be the corruption we’re witnessing in Washington. We need to take it on. That’s why I’m running for U.S. Senate.
No better way to begin the day than the MLK Triangle Interfaith Breakfast in Durham. Thank you to all those who took the time to chat.

Dr. King’s unwavering dedication to equality & justice—& his work to advance the rights of his fellow citizens—changed the course of our nation’s history. Today, we honor his legacy—and we recommit to living up to the call to be our brothers’ & sisters’ keepers.
Thrilled to be a part of United Way of Central Carolinas' MLK Call to Service this afternoon in Charlotte!
Enjoyed a nice breakfast with members of the NC International Minority Coalition this morning in Charlotte. Thank you for taking the time!
Medicaid expansion shouldn’t be a partisan issue—it’s a moral one. We could help more than 600,000 North Carolinians get the care they need. It’s well past time to do it.
If we’re going to make Mitch McConnell powerless, we need to win back the Senate. And to do that, we have to win in North Carolina.

Good news out of Virginia today—and a reminder that here in North Carolina, we are long overdue to ratify the ERA. In the Senate, I will support efforts to ensure it can take effect, because the story of North Carolina belongs to all of us.
Sen. Tillis voted not once, not twice, but three times to divert $80M in military funding from NC to pay for the border wall. Now more money & projects could be at risk. It’s unacceptable.
One of my favorite parts of running for Senate is the opportunity to travel the state I love. Great to be with friends in Greensboro last night.
A reminder that Sen. Tillis passed the law that stands in the way of expanding Medicaid in our state. North Carolinians deserve better than this.
To flip the Senate, we have to win in North Carolina. Together, we’re going to do just that.
As I meet folks all over the state, one message comes through loud and clear: North Carolinians are ready to replace Sen. Tillis. He’s certainly in for a tough fight this year.
When someone serves, their family does, too. My thoughts are with all those currently deployed and their loved ones here at home.

Unlike Sen. Tillis, who has worked to gut health care coverage for North Carolinians, I will fight to expand health care access and lower costs. That includes supporting efforts to finally expand Medicaid.
This year we’re going to replace Thom Tillis. And together, we’re building a strong team to do just that.  Thanks for a great 2019. Let’s gear up for an even better 2020.

As we travel the state, one thing is abundantly clear: the people of North Carolina are ready to elect new leadership, bring Thom Tillis home, and finally put this seat to work for them again. I couldn’t be more grateful for the support we’ve received.

Thank you to the Durham People's Alliance for having me at your candidate mixer. If last night’s event was any indication, folks are enthusiastic and ready to fight hard for progress in 2020. Let’s get to work!

My statement on the U.S. strike that killed General Soleimani:
When the president dials 9-1-1, the phone rings at Fort Bragg. My thoughts are with the 82nd Airborne and their families. Thank you for your service.
Thank you to everyone who helped us meet our end-of-quarter fundraising goal. Your support means so much to me as we head into 2020 strong—and ready to replace Thom Tillis. Happy New Year!
In just a few hours, we’ll head into a new year. I want to take a moment to thank all those who made 2019 so rewarding. I couldn’t be more excited to work together to win this seat in 2020.

‪For too many NC families, our economy isn’t working. It needs to change. When I replace Sen. Tillis, I’ll work to rein in the cost of higher education & health care, promote good-paying full-time jobs with benefits, and finally raise the minimum wage.
Happy holidays! Wishing you a season filled with peace and happiness.
The Cook Political Report is right: Winning this seat is key to a Democratic Senate majority. We absolutely can—and will—put this seat back to work for North Carolina.
Lexington is more than the town I’m from—it’s the place that made me who I am. I’m looking forward to bringing Lexington values to Washington (and maybe bringing some Lexington Barbecue, too).
Sen. Tillis allowed $80 million to be taken from our state’s military families. Then he promised those families the money would come—but we know now it won’t. North Carolina deserves better.

As an Army veteran who has been trained on firearms and a parent who drops his kids off at school praying they’ll come home safe, addressing gun violence and keeping our communities safe is deeply personal to me. I’m proud to have Brady’s support.
We need to win the Senate.

Senator Tillis has spent his career making it harder for North Carolinians to access health care, and today, thanks in part to his vote to support the GOP tax law, coverage for 1.7 million North Carolinians with pre-existing conditions like asthma and cancer is at risk. More than ever, North Carolinians need new leadership in the Senate to bring down health care costs and expand access, which I’m committed to doing when I hold this seat.

Today marks 6 months since we launched this Senate campaign, and I want to take a moment to say thank you to all those who've gotten involved since. We're going to replace Thom Tillis in 2020. And we're going to do it together. https://www.calfornc.com/2020

Wealthy corporations have reaped the benefits while too many NC families struggle to get by. In the Senate, I will: ✅Support middle class tax cuts and credits. ✅Promote good-paying full-time jobs with benefits. ✅Rein in the cost of higher education & health care. ✅Work to close the wage gap. ✅Defend NC's farming families against reckless tariffs.
It’s no mystery why Senator Tillis is “bleeding support.” It’s because over and over again, he’s proven he’s too weak to fight for our state. And that’s exactly why I’m running to replace him.

Enjoyed a great breakfast and discussion with the Rowan County Democratic Party this morning—talking about education, infrastructure, and how together, we will replace Thom Tillis next fall. Thank you to everyone who joined us!

North Carolinians are loyal, hardworking, decent, and proudly independent people, and we expect the same from our U.S. Senator. I’ll give you my word: In the Senate, I will always put our state first.
A great night at the Cabarrus County Democratic Women - Active Christmas party meeting! Thank you to all those who took the time to chat about how together, we’ll win back this Senate seat in 2020.

Earlier this week, I officially filed my candidacy. In 2020, I’m going to replace Thom Tillis in the U.S. Senate. I hope you’ll join me as we win back this seat.

Love this front page from my hometown paper. Lexington is where I learned the values that make me who I am: hard work, public service, fairness & independence. Together, we’re going to take those values to Washington in 2020.

Honored to be in my hometown, Lexington, after announcing I will file to run for the U.S. Senate. I would consider it an honor to serve the state that I love in the U.S. Senate, and I pledge to roll up my sleeves and work every day on the most important issues facing North Carolina families. PEBD: I took this oath 20 years ago today, when I enlisted in the Reserves: “I do solemnly swear that I will support and defend the Constitution of the United States against all enemies, foreign and domestic; that I will bear true faith and allegiance to the same; and that I will obey the orders of the President of the United States and the orders of the officers appointed over me, according to regulations and the Uniform Code of Military Justice. So help me God.” Fulfilling it has required a lot more than I ever imagined—and I have served with some extraordinary patriots along the way. But I’m especially grateful to my family. Even though they didn’t take the same oath, they served too. It wouldn’t have had the same meaning without them. Airborne!

As a veteran who chose to serve after 9/11, I consider North Carolina Republicans’ actions yesterday disrespectful and unconscionable. This is yet another example of the fact that our politics is broken and corrupt—and another reason why I’m fighting to fix it.While North Carolina Democrats were remembering the lives lost on Sept. 11, 2001, their Republican colleagues took advantage of their absence.

Like you, I’ll never forget the emotions of 9/11 & the days that followed. In the wake of tragedy, we came together around our love for our country & the values it represents. We reflected on our shared obligation to look out for one another—and we took it to heart. For me, that meant a call to serve. Within weeks of the planes hitting the World Trade Center, I applied for a direct commission in the U.S. Army Reserve. Today, I’m thinking about those who served in uniform with me, & those who are currently overseas. I’m remembering those we lost on 9/11, and the unparalleled bravery of the first responders who put themselves in harm’s way to save lives. We are called to serve one another—even when it’s not easy and even when it requires a difficult sacrifice. That’s how we remind each other that there is more than unites us than divides us. And it’s this American spirit that will guide us forward. #NeverForget

North Carolina is a beautiful State with a rich natural environment, but the quality of life we enjoy is under threat from many directions.  Our elected officials should be measured by whether we’re going to leave our State better for the next generation. In recent years we have faced two 500-year floods that have devastated Eastern North Carolina and coal ash spills that have damaged our rivers releasing pollution into critical watersheds.  Damage to our environment is also damage to our economy. Major corporate interests want to tack clean up costs onto our utility bills and are actively moving legislation to do so. With a former oil lobbyist in charge of the US Department of the Interior, now the oil and gas industry is one step closer to opening drilling off of North Carolina’s coast. As your Lieutenant Governor, I’ll be a leading voice in the fight against climate change and off-shore drilling.  I’ll be a voice for purposeful investment in the green economy and corporate responsibility.  The fact is, good environmental policies are also good job policies, now and for the future. This fight is personal to me.  For the last 6 years I have helped build and lead an environmental company that is taking on the challenge of landfilled waste and recycling.  My company has been ranked in the top 10% of mission driven companies in the world for the positive environmental work we do for communities. We can’t keep kicking the can down the road, leaving today’s challenges for future generations to inherit.  We are paying for the consequences of global climate change, bad policies and environmental degradation today.   We need change, and I’d like your support to be part of the solution. https://www.wral.com/judge-strikes-down-north-carolina-voter-id-ok-d-by-voters/18210695/ Basis for decision?  Gerrymandered districts led to illegitimate legislature.I served with the Army in Iraq and Afghanistan to advance democracy and voting rights, only to see them under assault here at home. As we see in the 9th congressional district here in NC, criminal misconduct can be ferreted out... with the possibility of new elections and people going to jail… What really stands in the way of free and fair elections? Over the last decade, Republicans have cried foul over “rigged elections,” stirred up fear of voting by noncitizens, and pursued “voter ID” laws under the guise of “protecting the integrity” of North Carolina’s elections. The fact is that these claims and policies are a distraction from the real rigging that’s been going on ever since they took charge. Why all this fuss? Because if you control the rules of our democracy, you control who participates and whose voices are heard.  And you then control what laws are passed and policies are pursued. As your Lt. Governor I promise I will never fold on voting rights. I will stand up for every North Carolinian’s right to vote in a free and fair election. Addressing the Forsyth County Democratic Party in Winston-Salem

Today marks the 59th anniversary of the start of the Woolworth sit-ins at a lunch counter in Greensboro. What started as four college students of color asking for service turned into a national movement.  Today also marks the beginning of Black History Month -- as North Carolinians, our history is fundamentally intertwined with the history of blacks in the South. It is also intertwined with the ongoing push for civil rights today. I was present on a brisk morning for the 50th anniversary of the Woolworth sit-ins and it was an incredibly moving experience. On February 1, 2020, I intend to be at the 60th anniversary. Today’s anniversary and the start of Black History Month are good moments to reflect on what it means to be a North Carolinian. I believe all of us are a part of this story -- black or white, gay or straight, native or recent immigrant -- that North Carolina belongs to all of us; we all have a role to play in fulfilling her promise and in making this the best place to live, work or raise a family. Today, let’s honor those who started a civil rights movement at a lunch counter and became catalysts for change. And then recommit ourselves to what each of us can do to continue the work tomorrow.
